WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.880
[Amit Varma]: India has been independent for more than 75 years and one question that we have to ask

00:00:09.880 --> 00:00:16.680
[Amit Varma]: ourselves is, why is progress so slow? Why are we still so poor and backward? In 1947,

00:00:16.680 --> 00:00:21.400
[Amit Varma]: we could say that part of our impoverishment was because of colonialism. We don't have

00:00:21.400 --> 00:00:26.240
[Amit Varma]: that excuse anymore. In terms of economics, it's clear that we chose the wrong path.

00:00:26.240 --> 00:00:30.220
[Amit Varma]: But we did a course correction in 1991, we had 20 years of progress with hundreds of

00:00:30.220 --> 00:00:34.880
[Amit Varma]: millions of people coming out of poverty. And while the last decade hasn't been great,

00:00:34.880 --> 00:00:40.680
[Amit Varma]: we can still turn it around. But on social issues, the pace of change has been glacial.

00:00:40.680 --> 00:00:45.180
[Amit Varma]: Women are still treated like second class citizens in this country and in their homes.

00:00:45.180 --> 00:00:50.480
[Amit Varma]: And we are still a society torn apart by caste. How on earth in the 21st century can caste

00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:54.800
[Amit Varma]: still play a role in our society? Well, maybe the eventual solution won't come from top

00:00:54.800 --> 00:01:00.520
[Amit Varma]: down thinking, but from capitalism and markets. My guest today is a Dalit scholar and doer

00:01:00.520 --> 00:01:05.760
[Amit Varma]: who has two great heroes, Babasaheb Ambedkar and Adam Smith. And he has this incredible

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:11.800
[Amit Varma]: line in his Twitter bio, quote, caste and capitalism can't coexist, stop quote. His

00:01:11.800 --> 00:01:18.440
[Amit Varma]: argument is that free markets, that network of voluntary actions, changes everyone's incentives.

00:01:18.440 --> 00:01:23.360
[Amit Varma]: And this is helped along by urbanization. We move to cities to be part of larger economic

00:01:23.360 --> 00:01:29.480
[Amit Varma]: networks where we can express some multitudes within us beyond our identities of birth.

00:01:29.480 --> 00:01:34.360
[Amit Varma]: It becomes costly to discriminate. Instead, our incentives drive us to embrace the larger

00:01:34.360 --> 00:01:39.440
[Amit Varma]: melting pot around us in our self-interest. Thus, over time, Dalits can escape the rigid

00:01:39.440 --> 00:01:44.200
[Amit Varma]: networks that bind them down in their villages, which Ambedkar had famously described as,

00:01:44.200 --> 00:01:49.160
[Amit Varma]: quote, a sink of localism, a den of ignorance and narrow mindedness, stop quote. Of course,

00:01:49.160 --> 00:01:54.560
[Amit Varma]: going to cities, markets are not a panacea by themselves. Change takes time. But it's

00:01:54.560 --> 00:01:59.720
[Amit Varma]: a process in the right direction. And it is a process in which two great minds have been

00:01:59.720 --> 00:02:07.320
[Amit Varma]: our moral guides, Babasaheb Ambedkar and Adam Smith.

00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:12.520
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:02:12.520 --> 00:02:20.320
[Unknown]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Bharma.

00:02:20.320 --> 00:02:24.800
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen. My guest today is Chandrabhan Prasad, a Dalit scholar,

00:02:24.800 --> 00:02:30.080
[Amit Varma]: journalist, writer and activist who is credited with coining the term Dalit capitalism. Chandrabhan

00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:35.200
[Amit Varma]: ji grew up in a small village, made his way to Delhi for higher education, went to JNU,

00:02:35.200 --> 00:02:40.000
[Amit Varma]: became a Naxalite, took up arms and later realized that while his fight for justice

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:45.080
[Amit Varma]: was an important one, the means through which he was pursuing it was wrong. He realized

00:02:45.080 --> 00:02:50.260
[Amit Varma]: the power of markets and cities in empowering Dalits, especially after the liberalization

00:02:50.260 --> 00:02:55.180
[Amit Varma]: of 1991. He has been a prolific columnist for this point of view and co-wrote the book

00:02:55.180 --> 00:03:00.080
[Amit Varma]: Defying the Odds, The Rise of the Dalit Entrepreneurs with Devesh Kapoor and D. Shyam Babu. He has

00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:05.060
[Amit Varma]: also written the books What is Ambedkarism and Dalitphobia. He was one of the driving

00:03:05.060 --> 00:03:10.520
[Amit Varma]: forces behind DICCI-DICI, the Dalit Indian Chamber of Commerce and Industry, and was

00:03:10.520 --> 00:03:15.160
[Amit Varma]: a visiting scholar at the University of Pennsylvania. These days, he is a fellow at the Mercatus

00:03:15.160 --> 00:03:20.440
[Amit Varma]: Centre and was given a grant by Emergent Ventures which has led to him writing a couple of forthcoming

00:03:20.440 --> 00:03:25.640
[Amit Varma]: books on the Dalit movement in India and, indeed, Dalit history. My frequent guest Shruti

00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:29.840
[Amit Varma]: Rajagopalan works at Emergent Ventures, so when Chandrabhan ji refers to Dr. Shruti in

00:03:29.840 --> 00:03:34.360
[Amit Varma]: this conversation, that's who he means. This conversation blew my mind because while

00:03:34.360 --> 00:03:39.400
[Amit Varma]: every non-blind Indian knows how pernicious the caste system is, the detailed lens that

00:03:39.400 --> 00:03:44.920
[Amit Varma]: Chandrabhan ji presented for me was an eye-opener. He gave me a new way to think about ghoonghats

00:03:44.920 --> 00:03:49.940
[Amit Varma]: and the fall of female participation in the workforce and sunglasses and ponches and moustaches

00:03:49.940 --> 00:03:55.040
[Amit Varma]: and long dhotis and even Indira Gandhi. All of these contain multitudes. And you'll find

00:03:55.040 --> 00:04:00.000
